            div(class="col xs12 md8")
                 div(class="c-cardBlue")
                        div(class="c-cardBlueContent u-textColor_1-darker lh30")
                            p There are three main phrases that are used when asking for a favor.
                            .mt20.lh20
                                p #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] Could you open the door for me please?
                                p #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] Could you hand me the folder?
                            .mt20.lh10
                                p #[strong “Could you”] is followed by a verb.
                                p #[strong “Could you”] is the more polite form of making a request.


                            .mt20.lh20
                                p #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] Can you open the door for me please?
                                p #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] Can you get me the check please?
                            .mt20.lh10
                                p #[strong “Can you”] is followed by a verb.
                                p #[strong “Can you”] is a more informal way of making a request.


                            .mt20.lh20
                                p #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] Would you mind calling the porter for me?
                                p #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] Would you mind parking this car for me?
                            .mt20.lh10
                                p #[strong “Would you mind”] is followed by a verb + ing.
                                p #[strong “Would you mind”] is a polite way of making a request.


                            .mt20.lh20
                                p #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] Do you mind if I shut down the computers?
                                p #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] Do you mind if I move the meeting to 1:00pm?
                            .mt20.lh10
                                p #[strong “Do you mind if”] is used to ask for permission.




